ce:section.ce:para:
The low-field dielectric and high-field polarization properties were further analyzed here. With increasing stretching rates, the gradual reduction in crystallinity results in an expanded amorphous region, which is conducive to a higher dielectric constant. Additionally, the increase in the more loosely structured polar γ phase (compared to α phase) enhances the dielectric response of dipoles under low fields, leading to a slight increase in the dielectric constant (Fig. S11). Concurrently, the maximum polarization (
P max
) under the same electric field also rises with the stretching rate, reflecting the trend in the dielectric constant. However, at excessively high stretching rates, the molecular chain relaxation cannot keep pace with the strain changes, resulting in reduced orientation and the formation of cracks and voids. This significantly increases the remanent polarization (
P r
), as shown in Fig. S12. As shown in Fig. S13, the peak of 0.2D is pointed at around 320 kV/mm, while the peak of 0.2D-0.08 is pointed at around 130 kV/mm, which is similar to the circumstance that happened in temperature changes. For stretched films, the unsaturated dipoles respond to the electric field and are unable to switch back. When higher electric fields, the electrostrictive force is strong enough to overcome the energy barrier, resulting in more reversible phase transformation and stable peak intensities of the curves [39].
